Total / 84

Illnesses that occurred after 5 Apr 2018 might not yet be reported due to the time it takes between when a person becomes ill with _E. coli_ and when the illness is reported. This takes an average of 2 to 3 weeks.

Investigation Update
--------------
State and local health officials continue to interview ill people to ask about the foods they ate and other exposures before they became ill. 64 (96%) of 67 people interviewed reported eating romaine lettuce in the week before their illness started. This percentage is significantly higher than results from a survey of healthy people in which 46% reported eating romaine lettuce in the week before they were interviewed.

Information collected to date indicates that romaine lettuce from the Yuma, Arizona growing region could be contaminated with _E. coli_ O157:H7 and could make people sick.

This investigation is ongoing, and CDC will provide more information as it becomes available.

